Roquefort

Target IP: 192.168.195.67
Challenge Description: Sit down with Roquefort and have a cuppa.

Reconnaissance


Performing a port scan shows the open TCP ports above on the target machine.

Performing an aggressive port scan against the open TCP ports returns the result above. The application on port 3000 seems to be HTTP. There is an FTP application on port 21, but it does not allow anonymous login. I will start enumeration with the HTTP application.

Enumeration

Port 3000: HTTP

Browsing to http://192.168.195.67:3000 returns the webpage above. The target machine seems to be running Gitea 1.7.5 on this port.


I performed a basic directory search as shown above and found interesting directories. The directory /admin sounds the login portal.


I tried default credentials such as admin:admin to login, but I had no luck. But I do have the option to create an account. I browsed to http://192.168.195.67:3000 to create an account. I wish to enumerate further to find more information about the target machine & application.


After registering an account successfully, I browsed to the /admin/config. This page contains the server configuration information. It looks like a user called chloe is responsible for running the application. On the target machine, the chloe user exists too as the SSH path is provided. I did not find any other users & repositories.

Exploitation


I created a new repository called revshell on the target machine with the account I created previously.


RCE is possible if the post-receive option is enabled using Git Hooks. I notice this option is on! Then I inserted my bash reverse shell payload in the post-receive option for this revshell repository, as shown above.


Then I issued the commands above to push the commit to the remote repository. This will cause the post-receive to execute. Before I executed the commands above, I started a listener on my machine at port 3000 to catch the reverse shell.


And then I received a reverse shell connection on my machine at port 3000 with the session as chloe, as shown above. Now I have a foothold on the target machine. Previously, I tried ports such as 80 but it did not work. The listener on the attacker's machine must be active on port 3000!

Privilege Escalation


After finding nothing, I was losing hope. I decided to check each paths from $PATH. And I noticed the /usr/local/bin path is writable.


I created a file called test and it worked. Running cat /etc/crontab shows the entry */5 * * * * root cd / && run-parts --report /etc/cron.hourly. Maybe I can create a malicious version of run-parts with bash reverse shell inside the /usr/local/bin path?


I created the run-parts with bash reverse shell script shown above in the top terminal. Then I started a listener on my machine at port 21. And bingo! After waiting for some time, I received a reverse shell connection on my machine at port 21.
